thought.text:
I've confirmed the bug. Line 38 shows: `enum Baz {// Enum comment, this will break after formatting}` - the closing brace is on the same line as the comment when it should be on its own line.

## Phase 5: FIX ANALYSIS

The problem is in `/workspace/oxc/crates/oxc_formatter/src/print/mod.rs` at lines 1107-1118, specifically the `TSEnumBody` formatting:

```rust
impl<'a> FormatWrite<'a> for AstNode<'a, TSEnumBody<'a>> {
    fn write(&self, f: &mut Formatter<'_, 'a>) {
        if self.members().is_empty() {
            write!(
                f,
                group(&format_args!(format_dangling_comments(self.span()), soft_line_break()))
            );
        } else {
            write!(f, block_indent(self.members()));
        }
    }
}
```

The issue is that when the enum body is empty (has no members), the code uses `format_dangling_comments(self.span())` with `DanglingIndentMode::None` wrapped in a group with `soft_line_break()`. The `soft_line_break()` allows the formatter to put everything on one line if it fits. But `DanglingIndentMode::None` just writes the comment inline without any indentation, causing `{// comment}` to be on one line.

The fix: use `.with_block_indent()` like `TSInterfaceBody` and `ObjectLike` do. This will force the comment to be on its own line with proper indentation, matching Prettier's behavior.

## Phase 6: FIX IMPLEMENTATION

